It shows only what the eye saw.

35:27.734 --> 35:30.334
This picture was taken with a flashbulb.

35:30.434 --> 35:32.834
That's a different pair of shoes.

35:34.334 --> 35:35.534
Yeah.

35:35.634 --> 35:38.234
We know there were at least two of them.

35:40.734 --> 35:44.134
You won't see it there.
The flash made them stand out in the dust.

35:44.234 --> 35:46.934
- You develop those pictures yourself?
- Yes.

35:47.034 --> 35:49.634
- Newspaper boys seen this?
- Not yet.

35:50.934 --> 35:52.634
Keep it that way.

35:56.934 --> 35:59.434
Al, when can we see the Clutter home?

35:59.434 --> 36:01.534
Why were the men killed in the basement?

36:01.634 --> 36:03.834
I'll talk facts, not theories.

36:05.634 --> 36:08.333
It happened around 2:00 a.m.

36:09.733 --> 36:12.833
All four were apparently killed
by the same weapon.

36:12.933 --> 36:16.533
Shotgun, 12-gauge.
Mr. Clutter's throat was cut.

36:17.033 --> 36:18.733
Before he was shot?

36:19.933 --> 36:21.433
Probably.

36:22.533 --> 36:25.633
All four were tied
with the same nylon sash-cord...

36:25.633 --> 36:28.133
...sold in most hardware stores.

36:28.633 --> 36:30.333
And their mouths were taped.

36:30.433 --> 36:33.033
How were they tied? What kind of knots?

36:33.633 --> 36:35.633
Can we see police pictures?

36:35.733 --> 36:37.633
- Find the murder weapon?
- Not yet.

36:37.733 --> 36:41.233
- Any clues or fingerprints?
- Lots. All belong to the family.

36:41.333 --> 36:44.632
They say that Nancy's boyfriend
is a prime suspect.

36:44.732 --> 36:47.932
- Is that what they say?
- He was the last one to see them alive.

36:48.232 --> 36:51.232
- Except the killers.
- Then there were more than one?

36:51.332 --> 36:54.231
- Were the women sexually molested?
- The coroner says not.

36:54.331 --> 36:56.531
- Why didn't the dog bark?
- He didn't bark?

36:56.531 --> 37:00.231
- Nobody heard him.
- Nobody heard the gunshots either.

37:02.131 --> 37:04.231
Mr. Dewey, in your opinion...

37:04.331 --> 37:07.131
...do you think it could have been
an inside job, sir?

37:07.131 --> 37:10.831
- Why didn't Mr. Clutter resist?
- Mr. Dewey, just a moment, Mr. Dewey.

37:11.631 --> 37:13.331
What about the hired man?

37:13.331 --> 37:16.831
His check was made out for $1,707.

37:16.931 --> 37:19.931
Mr. Clutter's first premium
on a straight life policy...

37:20.031 --> 37:22.131
...worth $40,000.

37:22.531 --> 37:25.531
Double indemnity makes it $80,000.

37:26.131 --> 37:28.831
And that makes it a strange coincidence.

37:31.431 --> 37:33.731
And that's all it is, a coincidence.

37:35.731 --> 37:37.831
I didn't catch your name.

37:38.031 --> 37:40.230
<i>Bill Jensen, Weekly magazine.</i>

37:40.830 --> 37:44.230
If you're not here to write news,
what is your interest?

37:45.830 --> 37:47.330
Fairly basic.

37:49.030 --> 37:51.730
What's basic about a stupid...

37:52.530 --> 37:54.130
...senseless crime?

37:55.030 --> 37:59.530
A violent, unknown force
destroys a decent, ordinary family.

38:00.730 --> 38:02.930
No clues. No logic.

38:04.430 --> 38:07.530
Makes us all feel frightened. Vulnerable.

38:08.630 --> 38:12.030
Murder's no mystery. Only the motive.

38:13.630 --> 38:14.930
Got one?

38:16.930 --> 38:18.530
I smoke too much.

38:19.230 --> 38:22.430
How'd they enter the house?
A key? Force a window?

38:23.330 --> 38:25.229
Probably just walked in.

38:26.029 --> 38:30.329
- Don't people around here lock doors?
- They will tonight.

38:32.829 --> 38:35.229
I know something's wrong here.

38:36.129 --> 38:37.429
I feel it.

38:38.429 --> 38:40.629
I don't know what it is, but...

38:40.729 --> 38:43.429
Mr. Clutter never allowed smoking
in the house.

38:43.729 --> 38:45.029
Sorry.

38:45.529 --> 38:46.929
Something.

38:49.529 --> 38:51.729
But of course.

38:52.829 --> 38:54.429
The radio!

38:55.029 --> 38:57.429
Kenyon always listened
to the news and weather...

38:57.529 --> 38:59.229
...before he went to bed.

39:00.029 --> 39:01.529
But where's his radio?

39:02.229 --> 39:04.529
<i>Since the night of horror, two days ago...</i>

39:04.829 --> 39:08.729
<i>... few people are seen on the streets
of Garden City after dark.</i>

39:09.129 --> 39:11.728
<i>To date, no clues have been uncovered.</i>

39:12.628 --> 39:14.528
<i>No clues whatever.</i>

39:16.028 --> 39:20.328
<i>It was generally known that Clutter
never had large sums of cash on hand.</i>

39:20.828 --> 39:22.627
<i>No expensive jewels.</i>

39:22.927 --> 39:25.427
<i>Nor even a steel safe in which to...</i>

39:27.127 --> 39:29.727
Perry, baby,
if you don't want that burger...

39:34.127 --> 39:37.127
You and your hotshot
prison buddy Floyd Wells.

39:38.227 --> 39:40.227
Big, fat safe in the wall.

39:41.427 --> 39:44.627
$10,000. "A cinch."

39:45.527 --> 39:49.127
Okay, Floyd's a jerk.
But we scored, didn't we?

39:49.427 --> 39:50.727
Perfecto.

39:52.227 --> 39:54.327
You call an 800-mile drive...

39:54.827 --> 39:57.426
...and the rest of it, for 43...

39:57.526 --> 39:59.926
...lousy dollars, you call that perfect?

40:00.426 --> 40:01.526
And that!

40:02.126 --> 40:05.026
You don't believe that con
about no clues do you?

40:06.426 --> 40:07.926
You worry too much.

40:08.226 --> 40:11.126
How are them cowboys
gonna connect us? Remember?

40:11.626 --> 40:13.026
No witnesses.

40:14.826 --> 40:16.226
I know one.

40:22.526 --> 40:24.826
You. You're a witness.

40:28.726 --> 40:32.126
Jesus, kid. For a minute,
I thought you blew your cork.

40:35.026 --> 40:36.426
You're so right.

40:37.926 --> 40:40.026
We're the only ones who saw it...

40:40.526 --> 40:42.624
...and that, honey, is our big ace.

40:43.824 --> 40:47.524
Because if they can't split us apart,
they can't get a confession.

40:47.524 --> 40:50.524
And if they can't get a confession,
they got nothing.

40:51.924 --> 40:53.024
Next move...

40:55.524 --> 40:56.724
...Mexico.

40:57.424 --> 40:59.624
- Once we beat it out of the country.
- On what?

41:00.524 --> 41:03.124
$43 and a smile and bullshit?

41:04.224 --> 41:08.424
You guessed it, Chief.
It's the smile that does it.

41:09.724 --> 41:11.624
Like it says in the commercials:

41:11.724 --> 41:14.724
"The family that sticks together
lives forever."

41:25.524 --> 41:28.923
<i>Officers investigating the slaying
have appealed to the public...</i>

41:29.023 --> 41:31.023
<i>... for help in solving the crime.</i>

41:31.123 --> 41:35.023
<i>A Kansas paper, The Hutchison News,
has offered a reward for any information...</i>

41:35.023 --> 41:37.723
<i>... leading to the capture
and conviction of the person...</i>

41:37.823 --> 41:40.823
<i>... or persons, guilty of the Clutter murders.</i>

41:40.823 --> 41:43.423
<i>A reward of $1,000.</i>

41:46.223 --> 41:50.123
What about the reward?
That's right, $1,000.

41:53.323 --> 41:55.323
Yes, sir. Where are you calling from?

41:56.623 --> 41:58.523
Yeah. Go ahead.

42:01.223 --> 42:02.222
Who?

42:05.822 --> 42:07.922
How do you know he was a foreigner?

42:10.222 --> 42:13.921
- I see. Thank you very much, sir.
- Another tip?

42:16.121 --> 42:17.921
He says he saw a foreigner running.

42:18.921 --> 42:20.921
How does a foreigner run, anyway?

42:21.021 --> 42:23.721
Just how many people
have tried to claim this reward?

42:23.821 --> 42:25.621
Just about everybody.

42:27.021 --> 42:28.921
A mysterious stranger did it.

42:29.421 --> 42:32.821
Hired killers did it.
A jealous neighbor did it.

42:33.721 --> 42:36.921
Seems like the only one
who didn't do it is the butler.

42:38.421 --> 42:39.321
Any luck?

42:40.421 --> 42:43.221
None of the Clutters had shoes
with a cat's paw.

42:43.521 --> 42:47.621
No diamond pattern, either.
Insurance money goes to the family.

42:48.721 --> 42:51.321
And this, Nancy Clutter's.

42:53.221 --> 42:55.621
Found it hidden in the toe of her slipper.

42:56.221 --> 42:58.121
Something must've scared her.

42:58.321 --> 43:01.620
All of which brings us back
to the motive of robbery.

43:03.020 --> 43:06.620
I can believe one man might work up
enough rage to do it.

43:07.120 --> 43:07.920
But two?

43:09.620 --> 43:12.920
Who would kill four people in cold blood
for a radio...

43:13.420 --> 43:17.320
...a pair of binoculars and $40 in cash?

43:18.420 --> 43:22.220
These days? Take your pick
on any crowded street.

43:24.920 --> 43:26.320
You ever hang any paper?

43:26.420 --> 43:29.320
I couldn't cash a check even if it was good.

43:45.219 --> 43:47.819
Easy, baby. Casual.

43:55.019 --> 43:58.119
Excuse me. My name's Hickock.
Richie. And you're?

43:58.219 --> 43:59.819
Sharp. Luke Sharp.

44:00.119 --> 44:02.719
I'll bet in school
they called you Look Sharp.

44:03.119 --> 44:04.819
See that gentleman over there?

44:04.919 --> 44:07.619
Would you believe a runt like that
is getting married?

44:07.719 --> 44:13.219
Well, maybe he ain't any Fred Astaire
but he's my best friend...

44:14.119 --> 44:15.819
...and I'm his best man.

44:16.519 --> 44:20.019
My wedding present to him
is going to be what you might call...

44:20.019 --> 44:21.519
...his trousseau.

44:31.518 --> 44:34.418
Ideal shade for an informal ceremony,
don't you think?

44:34.418 --> 44:35.518
Perfectly ideal.

44:35.618 --> 44:38.418
Of course,
we are a tiny bit oddly proportioned.

44:38.418 --> 44:42.117
I mean, the upper torso is so large
compared to the legs.

44:44.417 --> 44:46.117
I'm terribly sorry.

44:46.817 --> 44:48.817
He's not ashamed of them scars.

44:49.317 --> 44:51.617
They gave him the Bronze Star in Korea.

44:52.717 --> 44:57.217
Luke, have you ever been to Eden Roc?
In Miami Beach.

44:57.417 --> 45:00.417
That's where the happy couple
is shacking up for their honeymoon.

45:00.517 --> 45:03.517
Two weeks all paid up.
Surprise gift from the folks.

45:03.617 --> 45:04.917
He's a very lucky man.

45:05.017 --> 45:06.317
He deserves it.

45:08.317 --> 45:12.117
And with these, $192.70.

45:12.417 --> 45:15.117
Would you like them wrapped
and taken to your car?

45:15.117 --> 45:17.716
No hurry.
Deliver them when the suit is ready.

45:17.916 --> 45:19.016
Oh, no!

45:21.516 --> 45:22.916
Four silly dollars.

45:24.416 --> 45:25.816
We're awfully sorry.

45:25.916 --> 45:28.316
We'll have to come back some other time.

45:30.016 --> 45:31.916
I'd gladly give you a check.

45:33.016 --> 45:34.616
But then you hardly know me.

45:34.616 --> 45:36.916
We're really grateful for your courtesy.

45:37.016 --> 45:39.916
- If it's a personal check, perhaps.
- You're sure?

45:40.016 --> 45:42.916
- I wouldn't want to inconvenience you.
- Perfectly all right.

45:43.016 --> 45:44.616
Which bank would you like?

45:44.716 --> 45:46.716
It's immaterial, I'm sure.

45:48.116 --> 45:52.016
My driver's license, identity card,
insurance card, country club...

45:53.016 --> 45:54.616
She's a private number.

45:55.116 --> 45:57.916
- Was that $192?
- And $0.70.

45:58.816 --> 46:00.816
Would you care if I...

46:00.816 --> 46:02.814
- Never mind.
- No, please.

46:03.614 --> 46:05.714
Well, I could use a little loose change.

46:05.714 --> 46:06.614
I see.

46:06.614 --> 46:10.114
Suppose I just make this out for $280...

46:10.514 --> 46:12.314
...and $0.70, of course.

46:13.314 --> 46:14.714
Well, I suppose.

46:15.214 --> 46:19.114
Mr. Sharp, you're a brick.

46:24.114 --> 46:26.414
You're good. You're really good.

46:27.314 --> 46:30.614
Smooth. No sweat. No strain.

46:31.014 --> 46:32.914
- You're an artist, boy.
- Right.

46:33.214 --> 46:36.114
If you're getting married,
you need a wedding ring.

46:36.114 --> 46:38.014
- Why not two of them?
- Why not?

46:38.014 --> 46:41.914
Cameras, diamond rings, TV sets
are the easiest things to hock or sell.

47:35.011 --> 47:37.711
You know, there's got to be
something wrong with us...

47:37.711 --> 47:39.311
...to do what we did.

47:39.811 --> 47:43.311
Nobody, but nobody,
ever gets away with a thing like that.

47:43.411 --> 47:45.111
Will you shut up about it?

47:46.311 --> 47:49.811
I can't shake this feeling
that we forgot something that night.

47:50.911 --> 47:54.311
I don't know what,
something that belongs to us.

47:54.911 --> 47:58.511
You want to go back to that house
and look for whatever the hell it is?

47:58.611 --> 48:02.711
Because that would make us
not only crazy, but insane.

48:27.810 --> 48:28.710
Any luck?

48:28.810 --> 48:31.710
If they didn't leave any fingerprints,
you can be sure...

48:31.810 --> 48:33.810
...they didn't leave any murder weapons.

49:01.910 --> 49:04.709
People who used to work for Clutter,
going back 15 years.

49:04.709 --> 49:07.509
Hired men,
people he used to do business with...

49:10.709 --> 49:12.509
- Just keep talking.
- Upstairs?

49:14.109 --> 49:15.409
Don't look up.

49:15.709 --> 49:18.609
- See something?
- I'm not sure.

49:19.909 --> 49:23.909
Now you take the office side
and I'll go around the kitchen side.

49:58.908 --> 50:00.808
It's true, really true.

50:01.008 --> 50:03.807
We're on our way
and never coming back, never.

50:04.507 --> 50:05.907
And no regrets.

50:06.007 --> 50:08.307
For you. You are leaving nothing.

50:09.407 --> 50:12.207
What about my old man? And my mother.

50:13.007 --> 50:15.707
They'll still be there
when my checks start bouncing.

50:15.807 --> 50:18.307
It's nice the way
you think about your folks.

50:19.407 --> 50:21.507
I'm a real thoughtful bastard.

50:35.906 --> 50:38.406
'Morning, Bess. Coffee?

50:39.206 --> 50:41.806
Hey, Alvin,
that prowler at the Clutter house...

50:41.906 --> 50:44.006
...get a confession out of him yet?
- Yep.

50:44.106 --> 50:47.406
His confession proved he didn't do it:
Escaped mental patient.

50:47.406 --> 50:51.106
If he's the wrong one,
why in hell don't you find the right one?

50:51.106 --> 50:55.206
I've got a house full of women
who are afraid to go to the toilet alone.

50:56.706 --> 51:00.706
Bunch of gabby old women gassing away,
scaring each other.

51:01.006 --> 51:05.306
Somebody with a grudge done it.
Somebody who hated the Clutters.

51:05.406 --> 51:08.606
Nobody asked you.
Nobody hated the Clutters.

51:09.006 --> 51:11.206
Leastways, nobody that knew them.

51:11.306 --> 51:12.406
Phone.

51:15.606 --> 51:19.406
If this can happen to a decent,
God-fearing family...

51:19.506 --> 51:20.706
...who's safe anymore?

51:22.604 --> 51:23.804
Hello?

51:25.004 --> 51:27.504
- From here?
- No, from Topeka. It's urgent!

51:31.804 --> 51:33.304
Okay, Mr. Sandrew.

51:34.104 --> 51:36.504
Tell Alvin it's a prisoner. In Lancing.

51:37.404 --> 51:41.904
Get me a rap sheet on this man, please.
He mentioned the Clutter case.

51:42.804 --> 51:46.404
He wouldn't say any more
unless he was called out of the cellblock.

51:46.804 --> 51:50.404
I have the warden on the other phone now.
Might be a break.

51:51.104 --> 51:54.304
If it is, I'll be out to Garden City tonight
with the tape.

51:54.504 --> 51:56.204
No, phone's too risky.

51:58.904 --> 52:00.204
Hello? Yes.

52:01.904 --> 52:06.504
"KSP 1-4-3-2-3. Floyd Wells."

52:12.203 --> 52:14.803
<i>- I first met him in the penitentiary.
- Hickock?</i>

52:15.303 --> 52:17.503
<i>Yes, sir. We shared the same cell.</i>

52:17.903 --> 52:19.203
<i>Go ahead, Floyd.</i>

52:21.103 --> 52:23.703
<i>We swapped life stories and I told him...</i>

52:23.803 --> 52:26.203
<i>... how I once worked
for a farmer named Clutter.</i>

52:26.703 --> 52:28.203
<i>Did you work for him?</i>

52:28.603 --> 52:30.603
<i>Yes, sir. Ten, eleven years ago.</i>

52:31.103 --> 52:34.603
<i>Dick wanted to know if Mr. Clutter
was rich and I said, "Well...</i>

52:34.603 --> 52:39.003
<i>"...sometimes it cost him $10,000
a week to run his operation."</i>

52:39.403 --> 52:42.802
<i>After that, Dick never let up.
Just kept asking questions.</i>

52:43.602 --> 52:46.502
<i>How many was in the family?
Did Clutter keep a safe?</i>

52:46.602 --> 52:49.502
<i>Dick said how he was going
to rob the Clutter place...</i>

52:49.602 --> 52:50.902
<i>... him and his buddy.</i>

52:51.002 --> 52:53.501
<i>And how he was gonna kill
all the witnesses.</i>

52:53.901 --> 52:56.401
<i>I just never believed him.
I thought it was just...</i>

52:56.801 --> 52:59.001
What took him so long to speak up?

52:59.101 --> 53:02.701
Afraid of other prisoners.
Issue a pickup warrant.

53:03.201 --> 53:04.901
All points bulletin.

53:05.001 --> 53:08.301
We better make it for parole violation,
passing bad checks.

53:08.401 --> 53:10.701
If they know they're wanted for murder...

53:10.701 --> 53:13.901
- Yeah.
- The question is why they did it.

53:15.201 --> 53:17.901
Why did Cain kill Abel? And who cares?

53:18.801 --> 53:21.201
They did it, and they'll swing for it.

53:23.601 --> 53:26.801
If they did it and if we can prove it.

53:29.701 --> 53:32.201
When we cross this bridge,
we're in Mexico.

53:32.301 --> 53:34.101
Free, clear and safe.

53:34.801 --> 53:37.301
Fabulous Mexico.

53:58.200 --> 53:59.300
Mr. Smith?

54:01.200 --> 54:02.700
Mr. Tex Smith?

54:02.900 --> 54:05.600
- Cops?
- Kansas Bureau of Investigation.

54:10.800 --> 54:13.400
Is this your son, Perry?

54:22.000 --> 54:23.800
Yep, that's him all right.

54:25.099 --> 54:27.099
Gets his looks from his mother.

54:27.899 --> 54:29.399
Part Cherokee.

54:29.799 --> 54:32.999
- Will you have some coffee?
- When did you see him last?

54:33.499 --> 54:36.099
- Couple of years ago.
- In prison?

54:37.399 --> 54:40.599
I was just fixing to make some grub.
You want some eats?

54:40.899 --> 54:44.899
He was in for three and a half years.
He's been out on parole for six months.

54:44.999 --> 54:48.099
Well, then I guess I haven't seen him
for five or six years.

54:48.199 --> 54:51.199
That's not surprising though.
He's a lone wolf just like me.

54:51.199 --> 54:53.199
You can rest easy on one thing sure...

54:53.199 --> 54:55.599
...you won't be having
any more trouble with Perry.

54:55.599 --> 54:57.599
He's learned his lesson for sure.

54:57.599 --> 55:00.299
When he wrote me from prison,
I wrote him back pronto.

55:00.399 --> 55:02.699
"Boy, you take your punishment
with a smile.

55:02.699 --> 55:05.199
"I didn't raise you to steal,
so don't expect me to cry...

55:05.299 --> 55:07.699
"...because you got it tough
behind the bars."

55:07.799 --> 55:10.298
Perry's no fool. He knows when he's beat.

55:10.998 --> 55:14.198
You fellows have got him whipped forever.
The law's the boss.

55:14.298 --> 55:16.598
He knows the difference
between right and wrong.

55:16.698 --> 55:19.598
I taught my kids a golden rule:
Always tell the truth...

55:19.698 --> 55:22.297
...wash in the morning,
be sober and independent.

55:22.297 --> 55:23.697
I showed him how.

55:23.797 --> 55:27.397
How to prospect, how to trap fur,
how to carpenter, how to bake bread...

55:27.397 --> 55:29.097
...how to be his own boss.

55:30.397 --> 55:33.197
Yes, he's a chip off the old block, all right.

55:33.697 --> 55:38.297
I never had no trouble with my kids,
not as long as Flo and me was together.

55:39.497 --> 55:41.397
But she wanted the wild life.

55:41.997 --> 55:45.297
So she took the kids and ran off.
Turned them against me.

55:45.397 --> 55:46.697
All but Perry.

55:47.697 --> 55:49.497
I don't know what got into her.

55:49.497 --> 55:52.297
She started drinking.
Turned into a hopeless drunk.

55:52.297 --> 55:55.896
Started stepping out with young men.
I caught her once and I...

55:59.496 --> 56:01.096
Anyway, she died drunk.

56:01.896 --> 56:03.996
Choked to death on her own vomit.

56:04.696 --> 56:08.396
So I took Perry and we started roaming
to forget it all.

56:12.396 --> 56:14.396
I took him with me everywhere.

56:20.896 --> 56:22.796
How that boy loved me.

56:27.596 --> 56:29.796
At night, when it was cold...

56:32.696 --> 56:34.396
...we'd sleep cuddled up.

